00:01:00.336 --> 00:01:04.286 A:middle
And it can often be treated as
an afterthought by developers.

00:01:04.866 --> 00:01:06.756 A:middle
Not the developers in
this room of course,

00:01:06.756 --> 00:01:08.436 A:middle
but let's just say
some developers.

00:01:09.586 --> 00:01:14.676 A:middle
And when that's the case, it can
often take the form of an FAQ

00:01:14.676 --> 00:01:18.316 A:middle
or help system where
basically you wait

00:01:18.316 --> 00:01:22.866 A:middle
until a person gets stuck, drop
them into a comprehensive body

00:01:22.866 --> 00:01:25.946 A:middle
of content and then have
them fend for themselves

00:01:25.946 --> 00:01:27.206 A:middle
to try to get answers.

00:01:27.696 --> 00:01:32.326 A:middle
And historically, icons
like this have been used

00:01:32.326 --> 00:01:34.136 A:middle
to represent the experience,

00:01:34.476 --> 00:01:37.726 A:middle
which really isn't the
most flattering image

00:01:37.726 --> 00:01:44.096 A:middle
to have associated with your app
or game, unless of course it's

00:01:44.096 --> 00:01:49.866 A:middle
about rescuing people
lost at sea, I don't know.

00:01:50.106 --> 00:01:54.206 A:middle
Now, this Get answers
strategy, it does have its place

00:01:54.536 --> 00:01:59.136 A:middle
in help systems for deeper
apps, but as iOS developers,

00:01:59.136 --> 00:02:01.286 A:middle
you probably don't
even have to go here.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:01:59.136 --> 00:02:01.286 A:middle
you probably don't
even have to go here.

