Hi, everyone.

00:02:48.856 --> 00:02:50.946 A:middle
My name is Rachel
Roth and I'm one

00:02:50.946 --> 00:02:53.596 A:middle
of Apple's user experience
evangelists.

00:02:54.276 --> 00:02:56.566 A:middle
So today, we're going to talk

00:02:56.566 --> 00:02:59.516 A:middle
about onboarding and
welcoming people.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:03:00.286 --> 00:03:01.946 A:middle
Now, this term onboarding,

00:03:01.946 --> 00:03:05.336 A:middle
you may have heard it called
the new user experience

00:03:05.336 --> 00:03:09.856 A:middle
or the first use
experience or what happens

00:03:09.856 --> 00:03:11.306 A:middle
in a tutorial for a game.

00:03:12.136 --> 00:03:15.336 A:middle
And really, onboarding is a term
that's traditionally associated

00:03:15.336 --> 00:03:17.476 A:middle
with what happens with employees

00:03:17.476 --> 00:03:18.886 A:middle
when they first started
a company.

00:03:19.446 --> 00:03:22.306 A:middle
It's how people acquire the
knowledge and the skills

00:03:22.576 --> 00:03:25.436 A:middle
and behaviors to become
successful at their job.

00:03:26.516 --> 00:03:29.946 A:middle
Now, when it comes to an app or
a game, people are going to go

00:03:29.946 --> 00:03:32.026 A:middle
through a similar
sort of experience.

00:03:32.346 --> 00:03:34.966 A:middle
They need to figure out, you
know, how does the UI work,

00:03:35.456 --> 00:03:38.296 A:middle
how's the game played,
is this app really going

00:03:38.296 --> 00:03:39.186 A:middle
to be right for me?

00:03:39.816 --> 00:03:43.186 A:middle
And that's why you
want to welcome them.

00:03:43.186 --> 00:03:46.816 A:middle
It's so important that their
first experience is a good one

00:03:46.816 --> 00:03:49.976 A:middle
because otherwise it's going
to be their last experience,

00:03:50.946 --> 00:03:52.866 A:middle
because we've got a
million other competitors

00:03:52.866 --> 00:03:54.086 A:middle
in the App Store, literally.

00:03:54.736 --> 00:03:55.766 A:middle
So people aren't going to stick

00:03:55.766 --> 00:03:58.756 A:middle
around if the first
experience isn't really great.

00:03:58.806 --> 00:04:05.106 A:middle
Now, when you step into a store,
there's - like a physical store


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:03:58.806 --> 00:04:05.106 A:middle
Now, when you step into a store,
there's - like a physical store

00:04:05.106 --> 00:04:07.456 A:middle
in real life, there's a number
of things that are going

00:04:07.456 --> 00:04:09.676 A:middle
to influence whether
or not you stick around

00:04:10.096 --> 00:04:11.606 A:middle
or whether you turn
around and walk out.

00:04:12.726 --> 00:04:13.876 A:middle
You know, is the layout

00:04:13.876 --> 00:04:16.676 A:middle
of the store intimidating
or is it inviting?

00:04:16.676 --> 00:04:18.986 A:middle
You know, is the staff rude?

00:04:19.646 --> 00:04:21.926 A:middle
Is the staff really
aggressively pushy?

00:04:22.816 --> 00:04:25.816 A:middle
Those things could turn you
off and make you walk away.

00:04:26.396 --> 00:04:30.066 A:middle
But if the staff is inviting and
the environment is comfortable,

00:04:30.416 --> 00:04:33.396 A:middle
well, you might stick around,
explore the merchandise.

00:04:34.896 --> 00:04:39.096 A:middle
So the best approach with
apps or games is that you want

00:04:39.096 --> 00:04:42.196 A:middle
to get people in and using
them as quickly as possible.

00:04:43.306 --> 00:04:45.146 A:middle
You just want to let
people jump right in,

00:04:45.146 --> 00:04:48.966 A:middle
and sometimes that's
not always possible.

00:04:49.396 --> 00:04:53.576 A:middle
Now, there are a number of
reasons for having onboarding

00:04:53.576 --> 00:04:58.746 A:middle
and having a confusing or poorly
executed UI is not one of them.

00:04:59.556 --> 00:05:04.016 A:middle
So you want to make sure if
your UI isn't intuitive and easy


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:04:59.556 --> 00:05:04.016 A:middle
So you want to make sure if
your UI isn't intuitive and easy

00:05:04.016 --> 00:05:06.336 A:middle
to use, spend time
refining that UI,

00:05:07.246 --> 00:05:10.066 A:middle
not building an onboarding
sequence, OK?

00:05:11.076 --> 00:05:14.026 A:middle
Now, if you have
registration required

00:05:14.126 --> 00:05:16.936 A:middle
to use your application,
that's a different story.

00:05:19.036 --> 00:05:21.056 A:middle
Or with games.

00:05:21.896 --> 00:05:25.946 A:middle
You might need to explain
the backstory or the rules,

00:05:25.946 --> 00:05:27.536 A:middle
you know, how games are played.

00:05:28.356 --> 00:05:31.426 A:middle
Or if your UI is heavily
reliant on gestures,

00:05:31.706 --> 00:05:33.826 A:middle
that might warrant a
little bit of information

00:05:33.826 --> 00:05:34.966 A:middle
in order to get started.

00:05:35.746 --> 00:05:38.776 A:middle
So let's talk briefly
about if you have

00:05:38.776 --> 00:05:40.186 A:middle
to require registration.

00:05:40.956 --> 00:05:44.416 A:middle
Sometimes, it is absolutely
necessary to see anything,

00:05:44.486 --> 00:05:50.396 A:middle
like a banking application or
social networks or bill pay,

00:05:50.396 --> 00:05:53.536 A:middle
anything that has personal
information, then you're going

00:05:53.536 --> 00:05:56.886 A:middle
to need to let people
know what's going on.

00:05:57.276 --> 00:06:02.586 A:middle
But before, if there's any way
possible, you want to delay


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:05:57.276 --> 00:06:02.586 A:middle
But before, if there's any way
possible, you want to delay

00:06:02.586 --> 00:06:05.536 A:middle
that registration until
it's absolutely necessary.

00:06:06.146 --> 00:06:09.666 A:middle
Now, the iTunes store is
a great example of this.

00:06:10.186 --> 00:06:13.476 A:middle
You can browse and look at
all the books and the music

00:06:13.476 --> 00:06:16.426 A:middle
and the movies that you want,
and it's only when you go

00:06:16.426 --> 00:06:20.746 A:middle
to buy something that you need
to authenticate or register.

00:06:20.906 --> 00:06:23.696 A:middle
So this means there's
nothing standing in the way

00:06:23.696 --> 00:06:25.186 A:middle
of finding something you love.

00:06:26.216 --> 00:06:28.886 A:middle
Requiring people to register
before they can see anything

00:06:28.946 --> 00:06:31.936 A:middle
puts this unnecessary
obstacle in their way.

00:06:32.516 --> 00:06:34.826 A:middle
They have to trust that it's
going to be worth their while

00:06:34.826 --> 00:06:36.406 A:middle
to go through that obstacle.

00:06:37.686 --> 00:06:40.256 A:middle
Here is a better way,
this is "JUKELY,"

00:06:40.456 --> 00:06:41.796 A:middle
and it's a concert-finding app.

00:06:42.606 --> 00:06:43.906 A:middle
They've got a great design.

00:06:43.906 --> 00:06:47.356 A:middle
They'll help you find
concerts that are local to you,

00:06:47.356 --> 00:06:50.666 A:middle
tailored to your taste - they
will even find someone to go

00:06:50.666 --> 00:06:51.726 A:middle
to the concert with you.

00:06:52.686 --> 00:06:55.596 A:middle
Now, not only do they have a
very short onboarding sequence,

00:06:55.736 --> 00:07:00.046 A:middle
but they will let you browse
without registering at all.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:06:55.736 --> 00:07:00.046 A:middle
but they will let you browse
without registering at all.

00:07:00.976 --> 00:07:04.586 A:middle
You just tap that "skip this
for now" text at the bottom,

00:07:05.066 --> 00:07:06.426 A:middle
and you can go right inside

00:07:06.426 --> 00:07:08.336 A:middle
and explore what the
app is all about.

00:07:09.076 --> 00:07:12.126 A:middle
You can look at the concert
listings, read about bands,

00:07:12.706 --> 00:07:15.476 A:middle
and it's only when you
express interest in something

00:07:15.476 --> 00:07:18.306 A:middle
or you want to buy some tickets,
well, that's when they have -

00:07:18.436 --> 00:07:21.616 A:middle
they ask you to sign
up, and that's great.

00:07:22.406 --> 00:07:25.386 A:middle
This approach lets you see
what that app is all about.

00:07:25.946 --> 00:07:28.896 A:middle
You can explore everything,
all the concerts in your area,

00:07:28.896 --> 00:07:31.686 A:middle
and you only have to
register when you're ready

00:07:31.686 --> 00:07:33.046 A:middle
to take action on something.

00:07:34.256 --> 00:07:36.576 A:middle
People are going to
be much more motivated

00:07:36.576 --> 00:07:38.916 A:middle
and quite frankly
comfortable going

00:07:38.916 --> 00:07:41.906 A:middle
through that registration
process if they're confident

00:07:41.906 --> 00:07:44.426 A:middle
in the quality and the utility

00:07:44.506 --> 00:07:47.486 A:middle
of what your app
is offering them.

00:07:47.696 --> 00:07:49.966 A:middle
Now, when it's time
to have people go

00:07:49.966 --> 00:07:51.266 A:middle
through that registration,

00:07:51.936 --> 00:07:55.646 A:middle
you want to explain why you're
asking them to register.

00:07:56.216 --> 00:08:00.596 A:middle
So think about it this way,
let's say a stranger walked


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:07:56.216 --> 00:08:00.596 A:middle
So think about it this way,
let's say a stranger walked

00:08:00.596 --> 00:08:02.936 A:middle
up to you in front of
Moscone and said, "Hey,

00:08:03.426 --> 00:08:05.396 A:middle
can I have your email
address and phone number?"

00:08:06.096 --> 00:08:07.466 A:middle
You wouldn't give
it to him, right?

00:08:07.876 --> 00:08:10.086 A:middle
That's just creepy, and you
have no idea what's going

00:08:10.086 --> 00:08:11.696 A:middle
to happen with that data.

00:08:13.246 --> 00:08:16.666 A:middle
Now, that's exactly what
you're doing if you ask people

00:08:16.666 --> 00:08:18.646 A:middle
to register but you're
not telling them why,

00:08:18.646 --> 00:08:20.566 A:middle
and they don't know
anything about you.

00:08:21.996 --> 00:08:26.596 A:middle
It's especially important in
cases where you have to register

00:08:26.596 --> 00:08:30.696 A:middle
in order to use an app
because your description

00:08:30.696 --> 00:08:32.876 A:middle
in the App Store,
or word of mouth,

00:08:33.405 --> 00:08:35.376 A:middle
or brand awareness isn't enough

00:08:35.635 --> 00:08:38.076 A:middle
to make people feel
comfortable giving you all

00:08:38.076 --> 00:08:39.566 A:middle
of their personal information.

00:08:40.426 --> 00:08:43.846 A:middle
You need to make it really clear
what you're going to do with it.

00:08:44.616 --> 00:08:48.126 A:middle
So this is "Jelly" and they
crowdsource the answers

00:08:48.256 --> 00:08:50.146 A:middle
to questions from
your social network.

00:08:50.686 --> 00:08:52.586 A:middle
So they have a real challenge -

00:08:52.626 --> 00:08:54.406 A:middle
there really is nothing
they can show you

00:08:54.406 --> 00:08:56.206 A:middle
without you registering
and signing in.

00:08:56.656 --> 00:08:59.476 A:middle
So that's why they've given
you this brief explanation

00:08:59.686 --> 00:09:00.996 A:middle
of what the service is about


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:08:59.686 --> 00:09:00.996 A:middle
of what the service is about

00:09:01.706 --> 00:09:03.936 A:middle
and explain why they
need your information.

00:09:05.106 --> 00:09:07.816 A:middle
And very importantly, they let
you know that they're not going

00:09:07.816 --> 00:09:09.656 A:middle
to post anything automatically.

00:09:10.946 --> 00:09:14.876 A:middle
And this is very important
because when you're dealing

00:09:14.876 --> 00:09:17.246 A:middle
with people's personal
information,

00:09:17.346 --> 00:09:18.026 A:middle
you want to make sure

00:09:18.026 --> 00:09:19.776 A:middle
that they're comfortable
giving it to you.

00:09:20.106 --> 00:09:23.016 A:middle
They want to know that you're
going to protect their privacy.

00:09:23.016 --> 00:09:28.236 A:middle
And transparency around privacy
is particularly important

00:09:28.236 --> 00:09:30.476 A:middle
if you're dealing with
social network integration

00:09:31.086 --> 00:09:33.016 A:middle
because I'm sure we've
all had that friend

00:09:33.456 --> 00:09:36.656 A:middle
that he's got some app that's
going crazy on their timeline

00:09:36.656 --> 00:09:38.806 A:middle
and you're thinking, "Oh
what a noob," you know,

00:09:38.806 --> 00:09:40.086 A:middle
nobody checked their settings,

00:09:40.086 --> 00:09:41.296 A:middle
they didn't know
what they were doing.

00:09:42.186 --> 00:09:44.786 A:middle
And nowhere is this more
the case when you're dealing

00:09:44.786 --> 00:09:46.166 A:middle
with dating applications,

00:09:46.826 --> 00:09:48.926 A:middle
because that would
be a nightmare.

00:09:49.576 --> 00:09:51.996 A:middle
All of a sudden, all your
friends and your family

00:09:51.996 --> 00:09:55.126 A:middle
and some people that you kind of
know from work or met some time

00:09:55.126 --> 00:09:58.376 A:middle
in a bar could see who you
liked and who you didn't like.

00:09:59.096 --> 00:09:59.936 A:middle
Nobody wants that.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:10:01.076 --> 00:10:04.756 A:middle
So "Tinder" here is a very
popular dating application

00:10:04.756 --> 00:10:09.396 A:middle
and they're very explicit: They
are never going to post anything

00:10:09.666 --> 00:10:10.936 A:middle
to Facebook on your behalf.

00:10:12.036 --> 00:10:14.426 A:middle
And this is hugely
important because the way that

00:10:14.476 --> 00:10:16.926 A:middle
"Tinder" works is
they're asking you if you

00:10:16.926 --> 00:10:18.876 A:middle
like people based
on their picture.

00:10:19.606 --> 00:10:21.586 A:middle
So if you have any doubts at all

00:10:21.586 --> 00:10:23.286 A:middle
or you're feeling
a little hesitant,

00:10:23.656 --> 00:10:25.236 A:middle
you can tap that i button,

00:10:25.266 --> 00:10:27.236 A:middle
and they spell it
out in more detail.

00:10:27.846 --> 00:10:30.956 A:middle
They take your privacy
very seriously.

00:10:31.966 --> 00:10:34.606 A:middle
They're never going to
post on Facebook for you.

00:10:34.896 --> 00:10:36.576 A:middle
They're not going to
give away your location.

00:10:37.486 --> 00:10:40.036 A:middle
So people can feel reassured
and more comfortable.

00:10:41.116 --> 00:10:45.106 A:middle
And nowhere is this privacy
going to be more important

00:10:45.176 --> 00:10:46.876 A:middle
than with your social
integration.

00:10:47.306 --> 00:10:51.176 A:middle
Now I've just given you a whole
lot of advice about things

00:10:51.176 --> 00:10:52.966 A:middle
to tell people before
they register,

00:10:53.506 --> 00:10:55.806 A:middle
but I want to encourage you that
when you're telling them all

00:10:55.806 --> 00:10:58.126 A:middle
of these things, be succinct.

00:10:58.476 --> 00:11:00.486 A:middle
Be as succinct as possible.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:10:58.476 --> 00:11:00.486 A:middle
Be as succinct as possible.

00:11:01.366 --> 00:11:02.616 A:middle
We all know that people don't

00:11:02.616 --> 00:11:06.176 A:middle
like to read long passages
of texts on an app.

00:11:06.396 --> 00:11:08.286 A:middle
They just tap, tap,
tap and get going so.

00:11:09.286 --> 00:11:10.886 A:middle
"Uber" does a great
job with this.

00:11:10.886 --> 00:11:13.756 A:middle
If you haven't experienced
"Uber" yet in San Francisco,

00:11:13.756 --> 00:11:17.496 A:middle
it's a car service, so
they'll come pick you up,

00:11:17.496 --> 00:11:19.036 A:middle
kind of like a taxi.

00:11:19.766 --> 00:11:21.026 A:middle
And you might think,
"Well, why do I have

00:11:21.026 --> 00:11:24.316 A:middle
to give them an email address
and a phone number just in order

00:11:24.316 --> 00:11:25.956 A:middle
to get a ride from A to B?"

00:11:26.796 --> 00:11:31.256 A:middle
And they explain here very
briefly, they're going

00:11:31.256 --> 00:11:34.666 A:middle
to send you notifications
about when the car is coming

00:11:34.666 --> 00:11:36.526 A:middle
and emails about
the confirmation.

00:11:37.066 --> 00:11:40.726 A:middle
So that makes you feel better.

