00:22:24.666 --> 00:22:29.346 A:middle
Got it? If anyone got
that, I'm looking forward

00:22:29.346 --> 00:22:30.416 A:middle
to my latte after this.

00:22:31.006 --> 00:22:33.836 A:middle
But you can see how
difficult that is.

00:22:33.836 --> 00:22:36.256 A:middle
I'm sure you guys are all
tuned out on step three.

00:22:37.256 --> 00:22:39.966 A:middle
People are going to
be much more able

00:22:39.966 --> 00:22:41.216 A:middle
to follow those instructions

00:22:41.216 --> 00:22:43.096 A:middle
if they're parceled
out one at a time.

00:22:43.866 --> 00:22:47.056 A:middle
So if I said, "Go out of
Moscone, make two left turns,

00:22:47.756 --> 00:22:49.266 A:middle
and then when you
get to the corner,

00:22:49.266 --> 00:22:50.406 A:middle
I'll tell you what to do."

00:22:50.486 --> 00:22:52.906 A:middle
And then I'll say, "Go
to the coffee shop."

00:22:53.806 --> 00:22:56.196 A:middle
And then when you get to the
register, I text you, "Hey,

00:22:56.196 --> 00:22:58.316 A:middle
here's the coffee that
I want you to order" -

00:22:59.296 --> 00:23:01.016 A:middle
this would be so much easier.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:22:59.296 --> 00:23:01.016 A:middle
this would be so much easier.

00:23:01.046 --> 00:23:04.806 A:middle
So you want to give
instructions one at a time

00:23:05.346 --> 00:23:06.286 A:middle
and give people a chance

00:23:06.336 --> 00:23:08.546 A:middle
to apply those instructions
before you start teaching

00:23:08.546 --> 00:23:09.826 A:middle
anything else.

00:23:10.516 --> 00:23:12.906 A:middle
So this is "Leo's
Fortune," another one

00:23:12.906 --> 00:23:15.346 A:middle
of our Apple Design Award
winners from this year.

00:23:16.306 --> 00:23:19.746 A:middle
It's a really fun
platform adventure game set

00:23:19.746 --> 00:23:21.446 A:middle
in these really gorgeous
environments.

00:23:22.586 --> 00:23:25.626 A:middle
And their tutorial
level is fantastic.

00:23:26.166 --> 00:23:28.566 A:middle
They first start
to explain the game

00:23:28.566 --> 00:23:29.896 A:middle
with a little bit of backstory.

00:23:30.036 --> 00:23:31.646 A:middle
They introduce you to Leopold.

00:23:32.406 --> 00:23:35.116 A:middle
They let you know he's lost
his fortune and you're going

00:23:35.116 --> 00:23:35.946 A:middle
to help him reclaim it.

00:23:37.056 --> 00:23:40.216 A:middle
So this translates into
"get the gold coins."

00:23:40.566 --> 00:23:42.066 A:middle
Now you got your
objective, right?

00:23:43.556 --> 00:23:46.956 A:middle
Next step is just about
how to hold your device.

00:23:47.866 --> 00:23:50.406 A:middle
They're getting you used to
this idea that the left side

00:23:50.406 --> 00:23:52.576 A:middle
of the screen and the right
side of the screen are going

00:23:52.576 --> 00:23:53.596 A:middle
to do something different,

00:23:54.406 --> 00:23:55.896 A:middle
but they haven't told
you what that is yet.

00:23:56.816 --> 00:23:58.686 A:middle
Just put your thumbs
in this position,

00:23:58.686 --> 00:24:01.726 A:middle
and that gets you holding
the device in the best way.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:23:58.686 --> 00:24:01.726 A:middle
and that gets you holding
the device in the best way.

00:24:03.346 --> 00:24:06.046 A:middle
Now, once you press your
thumbs in each circle,

00:24:06.136 --> 00:24:07.616 A:middle
then they're talking
about movement.

00:24:08.136 --> 00:24:09.626 A:middle
What do you do with
your left thumb?

00:24:09.706 --> 00:24:11.656 A:middle
Well first, we're
just going to forwards

00:24:11.656 --> 00:24:14.206 A:middle
and backwards, the very basics.

00:24:14.206 --> 00:24:18.026 A:middle
And then you get a chance to
play with that a little bit.

00:24:18.026 --> 00:24:20.016 A:middle
You're going to collect
some coins, go through some

00:24:20.016 --> 00:24:21.026 A:middle
of the cool environments.

00:24:21.026 --> 00:24:24.886 A:middle
And then, a slight obstacle.

00:24:25.306 --> 00:24:27.686 A:middle
Now, there's a little chalk
drawing to help you out

00:24:27.686 --> 00:24:28.906 A:middle
or some words on the right

00:24:28.906 --> 00:24:31.256 A:middle
that lets you know now
it's time you're going

00:24:31.256 --> 00:24:34.746 A:middle
to use your right thumb, here
we go, get up over that ledge.

00:24:35.436 --> 00:24:38.476 A:middle
And then, a chance to play.

00:24:38.696 --> 00:24:41.696 A:middle
They give you things to jump
over, things to jump onto.

00:24:41.696 --> 00:24:45.596 A:middle
And next step, some
more obstacles.

00:24:45.726 --> 00:24:48.456 A:middle
Here, it's about using that
up gesture for something else.

00:24:48.856 --> 00:24:49.606 A:middle
So they're building

00:24:49.606 --> 00:24:53.986 A:middle
up the complexity while teaching
you one thing at a time.

00:24:54.186 --> 00:24:56.766 A:middle
Pushing up on that lever is
going to release the drawbridge,

00:24:56.766 --> 00:24:58.956 A:middle
and then you can
continue on your way.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:25:00.126 --> 00:25:03.626 A:middle
Then you'll learn about pushing
down and what that does for you.

00:25:04.816 --> 00:25:07.416 A:middle
So "Leo's Fortune" -
one skill at a time,

00:25:07.556 --> 00:25:10.776 A:middle
which is so manageable, and
it's fun because you're playing.

00:25:11.816 --> 00:25:14.006 A:middle
So it's a great example
of scaffolding,

00:25:14.766 --> 00:25:18.236 A:middle
along with "Hitman GO" and
several other examples.

00:25:19.826 --> 00:25:22.866 A:middle
So the first thing you do,
is you learn the objective,

00:25:23.786 --> 00:25:25.136 A:middle
collect those gold coins.

00:25:26.536 --> 00:25:27.576 A:middle
Next thing you're going to learn

00:25:27.576 --> 00:25:30.136 A:middle
about is the optimal
hand position, right?

00:25:30.206 --> 00:25:32.706 A:middle
So they're building up the
complexity with the scaffolding.

00:25:33.286 --> 00:25:35.686 A:middle
And the next thing
that you learn

00:25:35.686 --> 00:25:38.936 A:middle
about is really basic
movement - how to go forwards,

00:25:39.086 --> 00:25:42.546 A:middle
what are you doing
with your left hand?

00:25:42.716 --> 00:25:44.116 A:middle
Next step is obstacles,

00:25:44.606 --> 00:25:47.856 A:middle
which you conquer using your
right hand and various gestures.

00:25:48.416 --> 00:25:49.756 A:middle
And then further in the game,

00:25:50.426 --> 00:25:53.096 A:middle
they start showing you
advanced obstacles or puzzles.

00:25:53.186 --> 00:25:57.626 A:middle
So you can see how the
complexity builds up that way.

00:25:57.846 --> 00:25:59.606 A:middle
Now like I said, the
same thing applies

00:25:59.666 --> 00:26:01.236 A:middle
to apps, it's not just games.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:25:59.666 --> 00:26:01.236 A:middle
to apps, it's not just games.

00:26:01.566 --> 00:26:03.196 A:middle
You can teach people by doing.

00:26:03.226 --> 00:26:05.686 A:middle
You don't want to show them
a lot of screens upfront.

00:26:07.076 --> 00:26:08.966 A:middle
Now Pinterest - this
is Pinterest,

00:26:09.266 --> 00:26:12.156 A:middle
and they use onboarding
just for a specific feature.

00:26:12.366 --> 00:26:15.956 A:middle
So they have a new guided
search feature, and they needed

00:26:15.956 --> 00:26:17.436 A:middle
to teach people new to the app

00:26:17.616 --> 00:26:21.416 A:middle
and also returning users
how to go about using it.

00:26:21.416 --> 00:26:23.946 A:middle
And they do a great
job of parceling

00:26:23.946 --> 00:26:26.056 A:middle
out this information
one step at a time.

00:26:26.816 --> 00:26:28.726 A:middle
So the first time you
go to the Search tab

00:26:28.726 --> 00:26:30.286 A:middle
after this feature
was introduced,

00:26:30.286 --> 00:26:31.636 A:middle
you get a little
bit of information.

00:26:31.636 --> 00:26:34.126 A:middle
And they've given
you some samples.

00:26:34.126 --> 00:26:37.426 A:middle
And these samples are all things
that I'm pretty interested in.

00:26:37.526 --> 00:26:39.346 A:middle
So they've done a great job

00:26:39.346 --> 00:26:42.136 A:middle
in making this a really
valuable exercise for me.

00:26:43.146 --> 00:26:48.056 A:middle
Now I happen to like nail art,
and so next I tap, they explain

00:26:48.056 --> 00:26:51.366 A:middle
to me how to refine that
search even further.

00:26:51.976 --> 00:26:55.856 A:middle
And then once I've
done some refinement,

00:26:55.856 --> 00:26:57.996 A:middle
they talk about even
more advanced refinement,

00:26:58.336 --> 00:26:59.286 A:middle
free typing in.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:27:00.316 --> 00:27:03.026 A:middle
And because you're getting this
information one step at a time,

00:27:03.826 --> 00:27:06.156 A:middle
it's much easier to
understand what to do,

00:27:06.476 --> 00:27:09.096 A:middle
and they're letting you
execute on these instructions

00:27:09.206 --> 00:27:10.396 A:middle
so you're really learning.

00:27:10.746 --> 00:27:11.796 A:middle
You're taking it all in.

00:27:12.216 --> 00:27:13.296 A:middle
You're much more likely

00:27:13.296 --> 00:27:16.156 A:middle
to remember this later next time
you go to search for something.

00:27:16.696 --> 00:27:22.216 A:middle
With all of these examples,
it wasn't overwhelming, right?

00:27:22.396 --> 00:27:26.456 A:middle
And you're actually able
to use what you've learned

00:27:26.456 --> 00:27:29.126 A:middle
because you're playing
the game or using an app.

00:27:31.256 --> 00:27:36.216 A:middle
Because people learn better by
doing than they do by reading

00:27:36.496 --> 00:27:40.896 A:middle
or listening when it
comes to apps or games.

00:27:41.036 --> 00:27:43.516 A:middle
"Dots," "Hitman GO,"
"Leo's Fortune" -

00:27:43.836 --> 00:27:46.006 A:middle
they all reinforce what
they're teaching you with play.

00:27:46.836 --> 00:27:49.466 A:middle
And Pinterest was letting you
actually search for things.

00:27:49.466 --> 00:27:51.036 A:middle
It wasn't a canned experience.

00:27:51.086 --> 00:27:53.466 A:middle
Those were real search
terms with real refinements.

00:27:55.036 --> 00:27:58.766 A:middle
So even though this is
a really super easy,

00:27:58.766 --> 00:28:01.106 A:middle
can't-lose level
on "Hitman GO" -


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:27:58.766 --> 00:28:01.106 A:middle
can't-lose level
on "Hitman GO" -

00:28:02.516 --> 00:28:09.646 A:middle
[ Game Sounds ]

00:28:10.146 --> 00:28:13.616 A:middle
- it's a lot more fun
than this would be, right?

00:28:16.396 --> 00:28:19.196 A:middle
Now Benjamin Franklin has
a great quote about this:

00:28:20.086 --> 00:28:21.336 A:middle
"Tell me and I forget.

00:28:21.916 --> 00:28:23.086 A:middle
Teach me and I remember.

00:28:23.346 --> 00:28:24.866 A:middle
Involve me and I learn."

00:28:25.566 --> 00:28:29.276 A:middle
That's why you want to avoid
screenshots and modal displays.

00:28:29.976 --> 00:28:32.046 A:middle
Anything that's going to
take you out of context

00:28:32.046 --> 00:28:34.066 A:middle
or prevent you from
actually using the app

00:28:34.066 --> 00:28:36.066 A:middle
or game isn't going
to be as effective.

00:28:36.066 --> 00:28:42.016 A:middle
Again, what if this was the
experience with calculator?

00:28:42.016 --> 00:28:43.476 A:middle
It would be terrible, right?

00:28:44.016 --> 00:28:45.256 A:middle
First of all, the UI is

00:28:45.256 --> 00:28:47.566 A:middle
so dimmed you can barely
see the buttons at all.

00:28:48.326 --> 00:28:53.666 A:middle
Secondly, you don't need to say
tap here, tap here, tap here all

00:28:53.666 --> 00:28:55.056 A:middle
over a touch interface.

00:28:55.426 --> 00:28:56.536 A:middle
It's a touch interface.

00:28:56.756 --> 00:29:00.546 A:middle
You tap. And my biggest pet
peeve is when I see "Click here"


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:28:56.756 --> 00:29:00.546 A:middle
You tap. And my biggest pet
peeve is when I see "Click here"

00:29:00.736 --> 00:29:05.446 A:middle
on touch devices - ooh,
that really gets me.

00:29:05.926 --> 00:29:10.086 A:middle
Now again, if your buttons don't
look obviously interactive,

00:29:10.756 --> 00:29:11.886 A:middle
redesign your buttons.

00:29:12.636 --> 00:29:14.646 A:middle
Don't put some modal
display letting you know

00:29:14.646 --> 00:29:15.926 A:middle
that you can tap places.

00:29:16.446 --> 00:29:20.336 A:middle
So if you do need onboarding,

00:29:20.936 --> 00:29:23.436 A:middle
make sure that your experience
lets people participate.

00:29:23.436 --> 00:29:28.766 A:middle
And you can use animation
to do a lot of teaching.

00:29:28.886 --> 00:29:30.376 A:middle
It's a really powerful tool.

00:29:30.996 --> 00:29:33.236 A:middle
And there is a lot of great
information about the craft

00:29:33.236 --> 00:29:35.556 A:middle
of the animation in Tuesday's

00:29:35.556 --> 00:29:37.666 A:middle
"Designing Intuitive
Interfaces" sessions.

00:29:37.666 --> 00:29:39.276 A:middle
So if you didn't
see the session,

00:29:39.426 --> 00:29:40.996 A:middle
check out the video,
it's available.

00:29:42.336 --> 00:29:45.596 A:middle
For today, I would just
like to talk specifically

00:29:45.596 --> 00:29:49.206 A:middle
about something that I
see in games all the time:

00:29:50.236 --> 00:29:52.516 A:middle
the giant bouncing arrow.

00:29:54.936 --> 00:29:58.506 A:middle
Now at first, this does
seem like an effective way

00:29:58.506 --> 00:30:00.396 A:middle
to get people through
a tutorial level.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:29:58.506 --> 00:30:00.396 A:middle
to get people through
a tutorial level.

00:30:01.376 --> 00:30:06.406 A:middle
Great. But then, you know,
while it starts to show people

00:30:06.406 --> 00:30:10.306 A:middle
where to look, it eventually
becomes distracting.

00:30:11.006 --> 00:30:13.476 A:middle
When there's more information on
the screen, you're not looking

00:30:13.476 --> 00:30:16.646 A:middle
at the information, you're just
looking at the arrow and where

00:30:16.646 --> 00:30:18.906 A:middle
to tap and thinking, "I
want to play the game.

00:30:18.906 --> 00:30:20.246 A:middle
I don't want to read
the tutorial."

00:30:20.796 --> 00:30:24.236 A:middle
So you're looking at this
button instead of looking

00:30:24.756 --> 00:30:27.136 A:middle
at what the different characters
are going to do for you.

00:30:27.136 --> 00:30:28.156 A:middle
Why you're picking them.

00:30:28.326 --> 00:30:31.806 A:middle
The strategy of a game, or how
much it's going to cost you

00:30:31.806 --> 00:30:33.396 A:middle
or what the reward
is going to be.

00:30:34.076 --> 00:30:37.966 A:middle
So pretty soon, your game
has gone from, you know,

00:30:37.966 --> 00:30:41.866 A:middle
"happy ice cream fun time" or
whatever to "tap the arrow."

00:30:42.766 --> 00:30:44.446 A:middle
No one wants to play
tap the arrow.

00:30:44.596 --> 00:30:45.826 A:middle
That's not a fun game.

00:30:46.076 --> 00:30:49.336 A:middle
Tap the arrow gets
old so quickly.

00:30:50.426 --> 00:30:51.476 A:middle
Another way you can
kind of think

00:30:51.476 --> 00:30:53.386 A:middle
of it is I don't know
how many of you have pets

00:30:53.386 --> 00:30:55.816 A:middle
but if you've ever tried to
point something out to a dog

00:30:55.816 --> 00:30:59.106 A:middle
or a cat, they often
just wind up looking

00:30:59.106 --> 00:31:00.206 A:middle
at your finger, right?


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:30:59.106 --> 00:31:00.206 A:middle
at your finger, right?

00:31:01.516 --> 00:31:03.796 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:31:04.296 --> 00:31:10.676 A:middle
Yea. So this is exactly what
you're doing with tap the arrow.

00:31:11.076 --> 00:31:12.526 A:middle
People aren't going
to be looking

00:31:12.526 --> 00:31:14.046 A:middle
at what you're pointing
towards, they're going

00:31:14.046 --> 00:31:15.256 A:middle
to be looking at the arrow.

00:31:15.506 --> 00:31:20.496 A:middle
So rather than pointing,
try a suggestive animation,

00:31:20.496 --> 00:31:23.056 A:middle
one that's going to help lead
people's eye to the right part

00:31:23.056 --> 00:31:25.206 A:middle
of the screen or let them
know what they should do.

00:31:25.206 --> 00:31:28.476 A:middle
This is a really basic
example but it's a good one.

00:31:28.836 --> 00:31:33.076 A:middle
With "Hitman GO," you don't
need an arrow or a graphic

00:31:33.076 --> 00:31:35.966 A:middle
or some other kind of bouncy
arrow thing to let you know

00:31:35.966 --> 00:31:38.536 A:middle
that this is a button in
addition to being the name.

00:31:39.116 --> 00:31:41.556 A:middle
That pulsing animation
draws you to it.

00:31:41.556 --> 00:31:43.026 A:middle
It makes you want
to tap it, right?

00:31:44.076 --> 00:31:47.126 A:middle
I mean, they could have had
an arrow pointing, "Tap here,

00:31:47.126 --> 00:31:51.886 A:middle
tap here," but you
don't need to do that.

00:31:51.886 --> 00:31:54.666 A:middle
So that's what I mean about
using animation thoughtfully.

00:31:55.506 --> 00:31:58.466 A:middle
I hope I look forward to seeing
far fewer bouncing arrows

00:31:58.466 --> 00:31:59.076 A:middle
in the future.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:32:00.696 --> 00:32:03.706 A:middle
Now, if you do need your
onboarding, another thing

00:32:04.486 --> 00:32:07.776 A:middle
to keep - be wary of is
there is no need to point

00:32:07.776 --> 00:32:09.796 A:middle
out any platform conventions.

00:32:10.976 --> 00:32:12.866 A:middle
You only point out
the unconventional

00:32:13.576 --> 00:32:15.736 A:middle
because everybody knows
there is another screen

00:32:15.736 --> 00:32:17.746 A:middle
of app icons available
in this folder.

00:32:18.766 --> 00:32:20.726 A:middle
The paging dots take
care of that for you.

00:32:21.206 --> 00:32:23.456 A:middle
You don't - you wouldn't need
to put an arrow or some text

00:32:23.456 --> 00:32:25.956 A:middle
that says swipe to the
side to see more icons.

00:32:26.026 --> 00:32:26.966 A:middle
It would be ridiculous.

00:32:28.256 --> 00:32:31.596 A:middle
Similarly, you don't have
to tell people that tab bars

00:32:31.916 --> 00:32:34.026 A:middle
and toolbars are interactive.

00:32:34.276 --> 00:32:35.756 A:middle
They instinctively
look that way.

00:32:36.776 --> 00:32:38.716 A:middle
Or that you can swipe
for more content

00:32:38.826 --> 00:32:42.266 A:middle
because the content bleeding off
the edge does that job for you.

00:32:42.586 --> 00:32:46.236 A:middle
And that's really one of
the greatest advantages

00:32:46.236 --> 00:32:47.996 A:middle
of using platform conventions.

00:32:48.676 --> 00:32:51.566 A:middle
People will just instinctively
know how to interact with them,

00:32:52.086 --> 00:32:54.626 A:middle
so you won't need any onboarding
for these type of things.

00:32:55.456 --> 00:32:58.476 A:middle
You only want to point out
anything that's distinct

00:32:58.476 --> 00:33:00.986 A:middle
and unique and unfamiliar
to your audience.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:32:58.476 --> 00:33:00.986 A:middle
and unique and unfamiliar
to your audience.

00:33:02.206 --> 00:33:06.616 A:middle
Now, another thing to be wary
of is forcing people to go

00:33:06.616 --> 00:33:09.256 A:middle
down a secondary path that
they may not want to take.

00:33:10.096 --> 00:33:12.246 A:middle
So think about a
photo application.

00:33:13.376 --> 00:33:15.366 A:middle
I don't want to be
forced to crop an image

00:33:15.816 --> 00:33:17.546 A:middle
if I don't think it
needs to be cropped.

00:33:18.346 --> 00:33:20.236 A:middle
If I don't want to
apply a photo filter

00:33:20.236 --> 00:33:22.616 A:middle
to a photo, I shouldn't have to.

00:33:22.846 --> 00:33:25.746 A:middle
This is my app, I want to
do what I want with it.

00:33:26.496 --> 00:33:28.976 A:middle
Similarly, with music
applications,

00:33:28.976 --> 00:33:32.616 A:middle
it's great to show people how
to make a playlist or a station,

00:33:33.146 --> 00:33:36.426 A:middle
but don't make them market a
favorite if it's not a favorite.

00:33:36.906 --> 00:33:38.106 A:middle
That's just frustrating.

00:33:38.106 --> 00:33:43.056 A:middle
Now, when it comes to
text like I said before,

00:33:43.296 --> 00:33:44.976 A:middle
shorter is always better.

00:33:45.916 --> 00:33:47.686 A:middle
We know that people
are not inclined

00:33:47.686 --> 00:33:50.196 A:middle
to read really long
passages unless it's a book,

00:33:50.696 --> 00:33:55.266 A:middle
so make sure your language
is short and clear.

00:33:56.316 --> 00:34:00.096 A:middle
Avoid jargon and acronyms
or insider language


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:33:56.316 --> 00:34:00.096 A:middle
Avoid jargon and acronyms
or insider language

00:34:00.146 --> 00:34:01.186 A:middle
that may not make sense

00:34:01.186 --> 00:34:03.536 A:middle
to someone who's
new to your app, OK?

00:34:04.096 --> 00:34:08.436 A:middle
This is my favorite example,
"JUKELY," and they're talking

00:34:08.436 --> 00:34:09.775 A:middle
about their notifications.

00:34:11.206 --> 00:34:14.426 A:middle
It's so fun, a mixtape
from a stalker.

00:34:14.936 --> 00:34:15.886 A:middle
I'm excited.

00:34:16.755 --> 00:34:22.775 A:middle
I mean, this text is clear,
it's friendly, it's entertaining

00:34:22.775 --> 00:34:24.505 A:middle
as well as being educational.

00:34:25.076 --> 00:34:27.835 A:middle
So here are some
things you can think

00:34:27.835 --> 00:34:29.426 A:middle
about when it comes
to writing your text.

00:34:30.295 --> 00:34:31.906 A:middle
Ask yourself these questions.

00:34:32.906 --> 00:34:35.696 A:middle
Could the text be shorter
or could it be clearer?

00:34:36.065 --> 00:34:39.396 A:middle
Will the text make sense
to someone who's new

00:34:39.396 --> 00:34:43.025 A:middle
to the application, because
you look at your app all day

00:34:43.025 --> 00:34:47.116 A:middle
and all night every day, so you
really need fresh perspective,

00:34:47.116 --> 00:34:50.136 A:middle
and what will someone
unfamiliar with your app think?

00:34:50.616 --> 00:34:53.866 A:middle
Is the message too complicated?

00:34:54.315 --> 00:34:58.596 A:middle
If it is, you can make it
simpler, or maybe you need

00:34:58.596 --> 00:35:00.276 A:middle
to change your approach
altogether.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:34:58.596 --> 00:35:00.276 A:middle
to change your approach
altogether.

00:35:00.966 --> 00:35:05.606 A:middle
Or would images work
better than text?

00:35:05.746 --> 00:35:08.526 A:middle
There's our phrase, "A picture
is worth a thousand words."

00:35:09.376 --> 00:35:12.006 A:middle
Sometimes, it's just easier
to do it with a drawing,

00:35:12.586 --> 00:35:13.796 A:middle
like with "Leo's Fortune."

00:35:14.406 --> 00:35:17.746 A:middle
That little chalk drawing
is much - is a quick read.

00:35:17.746 --> 00:35:22.446 A:middle
You can hop up and go on your
way as opposed to saying, "OK.

00:35:22.446 --> 00:35:24.586 A:middle
When you get here,
lift your thumb up so

00:35:24.586 --> 00:35:26.306 A:middle
that Leo will hop
over the ledge."

00:35:26.836 --> 00:35:27.936 A:middle
That would be ridiculous.

00:35:30.056 --> 00:35:32.676 A:middle
And make sure that it feels
like an extension of your brand,

00:35:33.176 --> 00:35:36.306 A:middle
because onboarding is going
to be the first experience

00:35:36.306 --> 00:35:38.196 A:middle
that somebody has
with your app or game.

00:35:38.546 --> 00:35:40.566 A:middle
It's kind of like a
wedding invitation

00:35:40.566 --> 00:35:41.926 A:middle
or a party invitation.

00:35:42.196 --> 00:35:45.346 A:middle
It's going to set the tone
for the entire experience,

00:35:45.756 --> 00:35:48.716 A:middle
so make sure it feels
exactly like your brand,

00:35:48.916 --> 00:35:52.996 A:middle
like the personality
of your app.

00:35:53.246 --> 00:35:56.056 A:middle
And this is a very
important one:

00:35:56.906 --> 00:35:59.396 A:middle
Always give people
an option to skip.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:36:00.096 --> 00:36:04.146 A:middle
Always. If you saw the lunchtime
session yesterday, Natalia talks

00:36:04.146 --> 00:36:06.486 A:middle
about the dark days
of the interwebs

00:36:06.886 --> 00:36:10.456 A:middle
with the big crazy flash intros,
and all people wanted was

00:36:10.556 --> 00:36:12.016 A:middle
"skip intro, skip intro."

00:36:12.016 --> 00:36:14.766 A:middle
And that's exactly what
we're talking about here.

00:36:15.486 --> 00:36:19.516 A:middle
You don't know if someone has
used your app on another device,

00:36:19.996 --> 00:36:23.236 A:middle
if they watched their friend
use your app, or quite frankly,

00:36:23.236 --> 00:36:25.186 A:middle
if they're just impatient
and want to get going.

00:36:26.286 --> 00:36:28.806 A:middle
If people don't want to watch
your onboarding no matter how

00:36:28.806 --> 00:36:32.106 A:middle
awesome it is, don't make them.

00:36:32.246 --> 00:36:35.556 A:middle
And finally, learning should
be an enjoyable experience.

00:36:36.576 --> 00:36:37.566 A:middle
It's going to be pleasant.

00:36:37.756 --> 00:36:41.496 A:middle
Again, it's your first
impression of the app

00:36:41.496 --> 00:36:45.306 A:middle
or the game, so you want to
make sure that it's a good one.

00:36:46.546 --> 00:36:47.716 A:middle
Let's take a look at "Flight,"

00:36:48.216 --> 00:36:51.256 A:middle
which I think they have a really
great onboarding experience.

00:36:51.256 --> 00:36:53.876 A:middle
That Close button up there
is your option to skip.

00:36:53.876 --> 00:36:56.776 A:middle
And the UI is based
solely on gestures,

00:36:56.776 --> 00:36:58.486 A:middle
and so that's why they
wanted to give some -

00:36:58.546 --> 00:37:00.876 A:middle
just a very brief
onboarding explanation.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:36:58.546 --> 00:37:00.876 A:middle
just a very brief
onboarding explanation.

00:37:01.966 --> 00:37:05.236 A:middle
The text invokes
the joy of travel.

00:37:06.376 --> 00:37:08.056 A:middle
It's just a few short screens.

00:37:09.396 --> 00:37:15.766 A:middle
The visual design matches
every other aspect of the app.

00:37:15.766 --> 00:37:18.176 A:middle
And when you're all done,
you tap "Ready to fly,"

00:37:19.156 --> 00:37:21.166 A:middle
and you get a nice
little animation.

00:37:21.356 --> 00:37:21.986 A:middle
Fun, right?

00:37:22.216 --> 00:37:26.656 A:middle
Enjoyable, short and pleasant.

00:37:26.696 --> 00:37:29.206 A:middle
So make sure if you need
to provide onboarding

00:37:29.206 --> 00:37:30.716 A:middle
that you're doing
in a way that's fun.

00:37:30.906 --> 00:37:33.116 A:middle
Nobody likes a long
boring lecture.

00:37:33.756 --> 00:37:36.816 A:middle
So these are the things
that you need to strive

00:37:36.816 --> 00:37:41.116 A:middle
for if you need onboarding
- if you need onboarding.

00:37:41.656 --> 00:37:45.126 A:middle
Now, whether or not you
have an app or a game,

00:37:45.426 --> 00:37:48.456 A:middle
one thing that's always a
challenge is how to teach people

00:37:48.456 --> 00:37:51.556 A:middle
about gestures or
gyroscope enhancements,

00:37:52.176 --> 00:37:53.536 A:middle
anything that doesn't
have some sort

00:37:53.536 --> 00:37:56.126 A:middle
of visual representation
in the UI.

00:37:57.096 --> 00:37:59.896 A:middle
So let me give you
a few tips about how


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:38:00.006 --> 00:38:01.596 A:middle
to make the invisible visible.

00:38:03.086 --> 00:38:05.916 A:middle
And the first one is
using animation cues.

00:38:06.486 --> 00:38:08.916 A:middle
Now I know none of you are going
to make a big bouncy arrow,

00:38:09.826 --> 00:38:11.976 A:middle
but there's a lot of
things that you can do

00:38:11.976 --> 00:38:14.706 A:middle
to convey the interactivity
or the gestures

00:38:14.816 --> 00:38:15.916 A:middle
in a very elegant way.

00:38:17.056 --> 00:38:21.416 A:middle
You'll keep people focused
on the UI, not on the cues.

00:38:22.336 --> 00:38:23.536 A:middle
This is "JETSETTER."

00:38:23.906 --> 00:38:27.786 A:middle
It's an app that specializes
in luxury hotels and resorts.

00:38:28.056 --> 00:38:31.386 A:middle
And they've got tons of amazing
photography, which is one

00:38:31.386 --> 00:38:33.546 A:middle
of the things that sets them
apart from their competitors.

00:38:35.596 --> 00:38:38.876 A:middle
This gentle drift of
the photo lets you know

00:38:39.186 --> 00:38:41.536 A:middle
that it's interactive,
that you can touch it

00:38:41.536 --> 00:38:45.816 A:middle
and explore different aspects
of this stunning kitchen.

00:38:47.006 --> 00:38:51.986 A:middle
It invites you to touch it.

00:38:52.176 --> 00:38:55.646 A:middle
Now, the Withings health tracker
app uses horizontal movement

00:38:55.646 --> 00:38:57.466 A:middle
to show that the
screens are swipable.

00:38:58.156 --> 00:39:02.606 A:middle
So that - and if you don't
swipe it, it will auto-advance.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:38:58.156 --> 00:39:02.606 A:middle
So that - and if you don't
swipe it, it will auto-advance.

00:39:03.416 --> 00:39:06.856 A:middle
And they've got a nice rewind
page flip type of animation

00:39:06.856 --> 00:39:09.016 A:middle
at the end so that you know
you've hit the last item,

00:39:09.016 --> 00:39:11.306 A:middle
and then you can flip
through for anything you might

00:39:11.306 --> 00:39:11.716 A:middle
have missed.

00:39:12.246 --> 00:39:17.676 A:middle
And those are just some of the
ways that you can use animation

00:39:17.926 --> 00:39:21.016 A:middle
to really help encourage
people or explain gestures

00:39:21.016 --> 00:39:22.316 A:middle
or other aspects of the UI.

00:39:22.316 --> 00:39:25.736 A:middle
And again, there were
a lot of tips on this

00:39:25.736 --> 00:39:27.966 A:middle
in Tuesday's session,
so make sure to check it

00:39:27.966 --> 00:39:31.796 A:middle
out if you didn't
already see it.

00:39:32.056 --> 00:39:35.006 A:middle
Now, another effective teaching
tool is temporary hints.

00:39:35.446 --> 00:39:37.486 A:middle
Just really quick
tips about gestures.

00:39:38.626 --> 00:39:39.416 A:middle
This is "Yahoo!

00:39:39.416 --> 00:39:42.346 A:middle
News Digest" again, and
as I showed earlier,

00:39:42.346 --> 00:39:44.476 A:middle
their onboarding is all
about the core concept.

00:39:45.666 --> 00:39:48.606 A:middle
So instead, once you get
into the UI, they don't need

00:39:48.606 --> 00:39:51.456 A:middle
to tell you about
that ahead of time,

00:39:51.796 --> 00:39:53.026 A:middle
but they give you just a couple

00:39:53.026 --> 00:39:55.196 A:middle
of animation cues
and temporary hints.

00:39:56.006 --> 00:39:59.346 A:middle
So tapping on an article
headline has a horizontal

00:39:59.346 --> 00:40:04.976 A:middle
animation and then that
short message about swiping.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:39:59.346 --> 00:40:04.976 A:middle
animation and then that
short message about swiping.

00:40:05.086 --> 00:40:08.096 A:middle
So if the horizontal
animation didn't do it for you,

00:40:08.096 --> 00:40:10.916 A:middle
this message, which only
appears for two seconds,

00:40:11.146 --> 00:40:13.356 A:middle
makes it abundantly
clear that you can swipe

00:40:13.356 --> 00:40:14.456 A:middle
from article to article.

00:40:14.926 --> 00:40:17.816 A:middle
And you'll notice, they
didn't force you to swipe.

00:40:18.446 --> 00:40:20.746 A:middle
Because I might be interested
in reading this article.

00:40:20.796 --> 00:40:26.096 A:middle
They just want to make sure
you know how to navigate.

00:40:26.146 --> 00:40:28.166 A:middle
"Lightly" has a different
approach.

00:40:28.926 --> 00:40:30.456 A:middle
It's a photo editing
application,

00:40:30.456 --> 00:40:33.606 A:middle
and the first time you use
it, they give you hints

00:40:33.606 --> 00:40:35.236 A:middle
about gestures with short tips.

00:40:36.036 --> 00:40:39.736 A:middle
So here, I've just selected the
Argyle filter, and so what comes

00:40:39.736 --> 00:40:42.486 A:middle
up is a message about
adjusting the intensity.

00:40:43.246 --> 00:40:47.256 A:middle
Now, I just want to point out,
they don't actually force you

00:40:47.256 --> 00:40:48.536 A:middle
to adjust the intensity.

00:40:49.216 --> 00:40:52.496 A:middle
Any other - any place that you
tap will dismiss that hint,

00:40:52.916 --> 00:40:55.856 A:middle
whether it's adjusting
the intensity,

00:40:55.856 --> 00:40:58.556 A:middle
picking another filter from
the bottom or using any

00:40:58.556 --> 00:40:59.326 A:middle
of the other controls.

00:40:59.836 --> 00:41:05.006 A:middle
So in addition to
displaying temporary hints,


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:40:59.836 --> 00:41:05.006 A:middle
So in addition to
displaying temporary hints,

00:41:05.366 --> 00:41:08.746 A:middle
you can also think about
providing controls for people

00:41:08.746 --> 00:41:11.706 A:middle
to turn them on, and
this is what we do

00:41:11.706 --> 00:41:13.366 A:middle
in "GarageBand" on iOS.

00:41:14.216 --> 00:41:16.736 A:middle
Now, this is something
that's more appropriate

00:41:16.736 --> 00:41:18.266 A:middle
for deeper applications.

00:41:18.646 --> 00:41:20.706 A:middle
Not every app warrants this.

00:41:21.626 --> 00:41:23.996 A:middle
And you can come in and just
start playing these drums

00:41:23.996 --> 00:41:26.376 A:middle
and going nuts without
any assistance at all,

00:41:27.016 --> 00:41:29.776 A:middle
but if you want to know
more, get a deeper knowledge

00:41:29.776 --> 00:41:33.576 A:middle
about drumming, because it's
sort of a specialty case.

00:41:33.576 --> 00:41:35.416 A:middle
If you want to become
a better musician,

00:41:36.206 --> 00:41:40.606 A:middle
then using that question mark
button up in the corner turns

00:41:40.606 --> 00:41:43.006 A:middle
on these non-modal tips,

00:41:43.186 --> 00:41:48.436 A:middle
so you can keep playing the
drums while you're reading more

00:41:48.436 --> 00:41:48.966 A:middle
about them.

00:41:49.816 --> 00:41:52.466 A:middle
And without those non-modal
tips - without these tips,

00:41:52.466 --> 00:41:54.996 A:middle
you might not realize that
you can get different sounds

00:41:54.996 --> 00:41:59.616 A:middle
out of the hi-hat based on where
it is that you're tapping it,

00:41:59.616 --> 00:42:02.256 A:middle
or that a single tap will
play the crash cymbal


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:41:59.616 --> 00:42:02.256 A:middle
or that a single tap will
play the crash cymbal

00:42:02.346 --> 00:42:06.326 A:middle
and the bass drum together, but
a two-finger tap is what results

00:42:06.636 --> 00:42:07.926 A:middle
in just the crash cymbal.

00:42:08.536 --> 00:42:11.076 A:middle
Or you wouldn't know
that the speed

00:42:11.076 --> 00:42:13.306 A:middle
of the drum repeat is
determined by the distance

00:42:13.306 --> 00:42:14.436 A:middle
between your two fingers.

00:42:14.716 --> 00:42:15.776 A:middle
All really useful.

00:42:15.856 --> 00:42:19.116 A:middle
So if you think you
have an audience

00:42:19.116 --> 00:42:21.996 A:middle
that wants a deeper knowledge
or needs extra guidance

00:42:21.996 --> 00:42:27.426 A:middle
on a specialized subject,
this could be a good method.

00:42:27.426 --> 00:42:30.766 A:middle
And it's really important that
you can continue to use the app

00:42:31.076 --> 00:42:32.686 A:middle
so that you can learn by doing.

00:42:33.896 --> 00:42:38.996 A:middle
You can put it into
practice right on the spot.

00:42:38.996 --> 00:42:41.416 A:middle
Because all of these
approaches work best

00:42:41.416 --> 00:42:42.856 A:middle
if they're shown in context.

00:42:43.426 --> 00:42:46.016 A:middle
It's important that when
you're demonstrating gestures,

00:42:46.266 --> 00:42:47.706 A:middle
you want to do it
right in the moment

00:42:47.706 --> 00:42:50.136 A:middle
when people can experiment
with them

00:42:50.136 --> 00:42:51.446 A:middle
so that they're learning
by doing.

00:42:52.266 --> 00:42:57.356 A:middle
So now, I would like to address
a dirty word in iOS UI design.

00:42:58.806 --> 00:43:00.726 A:middle
Help. Help.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:42:58.806 --> 00:43:00.726 A:middle
Help. Help.

00:43:01.916 --> 00:43:04.376 A:middle
Nobody wants to think
they need help,

00:43:04.376 --> 00:43:05.906 A:middle
or nobody wants to ask for help.

00:43:06.416 --> 00:43:10.906 A:middle
And as a designer, I certainly
hope that every aspect

00:43:10.906 --> 00:43:14.566 A:middle
of my UI is intuitive
to use to every person

00:43:14.986 --> 00:43:17.796 A:middle
in every scenario no
matter what their needs.

00:43:18.286 --> 00:43:22.096 A:middle
But sometimes, this
is hard to achieve.

00:43:23.486 --> 00:43:25.936 A:middle
I mean, people have
different experiences,

00:43:26.126 --> 00:43:27.096 A:middle
different backgrounds.

00:43:27.726 --> 00:43:28.996 A:middle
They come from different
cultures.

00:43:29.586 --> 00:43:31.316 A:middle
They may have a lot
of experience

00:43:31.316 --> 00:43:35.756 A:middle
with the Apple platform but not
with iOS or specialty knowledge.

00:43:36.316 --> 00:43:38.836 A:middle
Like, I can navigate
around just about any app

00:43:39.146 --> 00:43:42.146 A:middle
on the Apple platform but
I'm not a good photographer.

00:43:42.616 --> 00:43:44.826 A:middle
So all those filters
and photo effects,

00:43:44.826 --> 00:43:47.126 A:middle
I don't know what
to do with them.

00:43:47.176 --> 00:43:49.256 A:middle
I don't know when I should
use them, how they're going

00:43:49.256 --> 00:43:50.526 A:middle
to make my pictures better.

00:43:50.526 --> 00:43:54.166 A:middle
And that's where help
can be very handy.

00:43:55.216 --> 00:43:58.576 A:middle
But it's not so as to feel like
a lecture from a mean teacher.

00:43:59.376 --> 00:44:02.146 A:middle
Or boring.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:43:59.376 --> 00:44:02.146 A:middle
Or boring.

00:44:02.426 --> 00:44:03.676 A:middle
Nobody wants boring.

00:44:04.516 --> 00:44:07.486 A:middle
We're moving away from that
large reference manual, right?

00:44:08.426 --> 00:44:09.506 A:middle
It should feel more like this.

00:44:10.296 --> 00:44:12.716 A:middle
Just making things a
little bit easier on people.

00:44:13.506 --> 00:44:17.196 A:middle
Or maybe like support from
a friend or a family member,

00:44:17.236 --> 00:44:18.386 A:middle
just giving you a
couple of tips,

00:44:19.446 --> 00:44:21.166 A:middle
because I'm definitely
not suggesting

00:44:21.166 --> 00:44:24.906 A:middle
that you add a huge reference
document to your app.

00:44:24.956 --> 00:44:27.596 A:middle
There are a lot of ways
that you can provide help

00:44:27.966 --> 00:44:30.226 A:middle
without people even
realizing that they got any.

00:44:30.226 --> 00:44:34.816 A:middle
One of the easiest
things that you can do is

00:44:34.816 --> 00:44:37.296 A:middle
to put instructions in
your empty containers.

00:44:38.136 --> 00:44:42.296 A:middle
Rather than just saying "no
results for search" or "nothing

00:44:42.296 --> 00:44:45.206 A:middle
to see here," you want
to keep an empty view

00:44:45.206 --> 00:44:46.276 A:middle
from being a dead end.

00:44:46.786 --> 00:44:51.316 A:middle
If it all possible, let people
know what to expect here or how

00:44:51.316 --> 00:44:53.206 A:middle
to get out of this
dead-end situation.

00:44:54.876 --> 00:44:57.986 A:middle
So in iMovie for iOS,
there is a theater view

00:44:57.986 --> 00:45:02.256 A:middle
